\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Model
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Model"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This section presents a Schumpeterian model featuring growth through creative
 destruction by entrants, as well as the possibility for incumbent monopolist
 of researching a defensive technology that increases research costs for
 entrants.
 In what follows, I first present a single-sector model to clarify the mechanism
 at play within each sector in the economy, and show that increases in the
 markup, capturing concentration in reduced form, lead to a larger amount
 of resources devoted to defensive innovation.
 Then, I move to consider a two-sector model, where each sector is identical
 to the single-sector model.
 I show that increasing markups in one of the two sectors of the economy
 lead to a misallocation of R&D resources towards defensive innovation in
 the less competitive sector.
 In order to illustrate the properties of the demand for inventors, I first
 analyze a single-sector partial-equilibrium version of the model, where
 labor supply of inventors and production is perfectly elastic at a fixed
 wage.
 I then consider a two-sector model where wages are determined in equilibrium,
 and the supply of inventors is assumed to be fixed in each instant.
 Proofs are reported in Appendix 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "app: Omitted-Proofs"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the empirical analysis above I used the HHI as a measure of concentration
 and market power.
 Appendix 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "app:Using-the-Lerner"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 shows that the Lerner Index from NBER-CES, a standard measure of markups,
 is strongly correlated with the HHI in my sample, justifying the reduced-form
 mapping that adopt in what follows.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Environment: a Single-sector Model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The consumption good in the economy in each instant is a Cobb-Douglas aggregate
 of a measure-one continuum of products:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Y_{t}=\int_{0}^{1}y_{t}(i)\mathrm{d}i
\]

\end_inset

The consumption good in the economy is taken as the numeraire.
 The market for each product 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{t}(i)$
\end_inset

 consists of a monopolist and a fringe of competitors.
 In what follows, I focus on a single market, dropping the argument 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 Competitors can produce using a linear technology with labor requirement
 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{t}$
\end_inset

, while the incumbent has labor requirement 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{c_{t}}{\phi}$
\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi>1$
\end_inset

.
 In this section, the labor supply is assumed perfectly elastic at 
\begin_inset Formula $w=1$
\end_inset

.
 Given these assumption, the monopolist sets the limit price 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{t}=c_{t}$
\end_inset

 realizing profits:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Pi_{t}=\left(c_{t}-\frac{c_{t}}{\phi}\right)y_{t}=\left(\frac{\phi-1}{\phi}\right)c_{t}y_{t},
\]

\end_inset

By the Cobb-Douglas assumption on the final good, the demand for each product
 is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
y_{t}=\frac{Y_{t}}{p_{t}}=\frac{Y_{t}}{c_{t}}
\]

\end_inset

Giving the normalized profit:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\Pi_{t}}{Y_{t}}\equiv\pi_{i}=\left(\frac{\phi_{i}-1}{\phi_{i}}\right).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Innovation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose that competitors can realize an innovation reducing unit costs to
 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{c_{t}}{\left(1+\eta\right)\phi}$
\end_inset

 investing in inventors at unit cost 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta$
\end_inset

.
 When one of the competitors succeed in replacing the incumbent monopolist,
 the other competitors can immediately realize a cost reduction to 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{c_{t}}{1+\eta}$
\end_inset

, so that the gap between monopolist and followers is fixed at 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 regardless of followers' innovations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Incumbents can in turn invest in a defensive technology that lowers the
 productivity of followers' inventors, by a factor 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega>1$
\end_inset

.
 I assume that this investment is completely unproductive, capturing a defensive
 patent that is unused by the incumbent.
 This defensive investment can be done only once, and is lost at rate 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 (the degree of patent protection).
 The incumbents' problem in normalized units as a function of the state
 capturing entrant costs is then:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\rho v(1) & =\max_{x_{I}}\left(\frac{\phi_{i}-1}{\phi_{i}}\right)-\alpha_{I}\frac{x_{I}^{2}}{2}+x_{I}\left(v(\omega)-v(1)\right)-x_{e,1}\left(v(1)\right)\\
\rho v(\omega) & =\left(\frac{\phi_{i}-1}{\phi_{i}}\right)+\delta\left(v(1)-v(\omega)\right)-x_{e,\omega}\left(v(\omega)\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Equations for generic 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\rho V^{I}(1) & =\max_{x_{I}}\left(\frac{\phi_{i}-1}{\phi_{i}}\right)-\alpha_{I}\frac{x_{I}^{\gamma}}{\gamma}+x_{I}\left(V(\omega)-V(1)\right)-x_{e,1}\left(V^{I}(1)\right)\\
\rho V^{I}(\omega) & =\left(\frac{\phi_{i}-1}{\phi_{i}}\right)+\delta\left(V(1)-V(\omega)\right)-x_{e,\omega}\left(V^{I}(\omega)\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

The optimal RD effort by the incumbent solves:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\alpha_{I}x_{I}^{\gamma-1}=\left(V(\omega)-V(1)\right)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x_{I}=\left(\frac{V(\omega)-V(1)}{\alpha_{I}}\right)^{\frac{1}{\gamma-1}}
\]

\end_inset

The value function is then:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\rho V^{I}(1) & =\left(\frac{\phi_{i}-1}{\phi_{i}}\right)-\alpha_{I}\frac{\left(\frac{V(\omega)-V(1)}{\alpha_{I}}\right)^{\frac{\gamma}{\gamma-1}}}{\gamma}+\left(\frac{V(\omega)-V(1)}{\alpha_{I}}\right)^{\frac{1}{\gamma-1}}\left(V(\omega)-V(1)\right)-x_{e,1}\left(V^{I}(1)\right)\\
 & =\left(\frac{\phi_{i}-1}{\phi_{i}}\right)-\frac{1}{\alpha_{I}^{\frac{1}{\gamma-1}}}\frac{\left(V(\omega)-V(1)\right)^{\frac{\gamma}{\gamma-1}}}{\gamma}+\frac{1}{\alpha_{I}^{\frac{1}{\gamma-1}}}\left(V(\omega)-V(1)\right)^{\frac{\gamma}{\gamma-1}}-x_{e,1}\left(V^{I}(1)\right)\\
 & =\left(\frac{\phi_{i}-1}{\phi_{i}}\right)+\frac{\gamma-1}{\gamma}\frac{\left(V(\omega)-V(1)\right)^{\frac{\gamma}{\gamma-1}}}{\alpha_{I}^{\frac{1}{\gamma-1}}}-x_{e,1}\left(V^{I}(1)\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

When successful, entrants obtains the unprotected monopoly position, that
 is, they destroy any existing patent barrier and obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $v(1)$
\end_inset

.
 I assume that the research costs of each atomistic entrant are linear in
 the individual research effort, as well in the innovation intensity of
 other entrants, capturing crowding externalities:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
C\left(x_{e,\omega,i}\right)=\zeta\omega x_{e,\omega,i}x_{e,\omega}.
\]

\end_inset

The maximization problem of an entrant in each state 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 is then:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\max_{x_{e,\omega,i}}x_{e,\omega,i}v(1)-\zeta\omega x_{e,\omega,i}x_{e,\omega}.
\]

\end_inset

The total research effort by entrants in the sector is then:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x_{e,\omega}=\frac{v(1)}{\omega\zeta},
\]

\end_inset

With quadratic costs, the optimal investment for the incumbent is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x_{I}=\bm{1}\left\{ v(\omega)-v(1)>0\right\} \frac{v(\omega)-v(1)}{\alpha_{I}}.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Consider first the second equation.
 That gives:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\left(\rho+\delta\right)v(\omega) & =\left(\frac{\phi_{i}-1}{\phi_{i}}\right)+\delta\left(v(1)\right)-\frac{v(1)}{\zeta\omega}\left(v(\omega)\right)\\
\left(\rho+\delta+\frac{v(1)}{\zeta\omega}\right)v(\omega) & =\left(\frac{\phi_{i}-1}{\phi_{i}}\right)+\delta\left(v(1)\right)\\
v(\omega) & =\left(\rho+\delta+\frac{v(1)}{\zeta\omega}\right)^{-1}\left[\left(\frac{\phi_{i}-1}{\phi_{i}}\right)+\delta\left(v(1)\right)\right]
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Then:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho v(1)=\left(\frac{\phi_{i}-1}{\phi_{i}}\right)+\frac{\left(v(\omega)-v(1)\right)^{2}}{2\alpha_{I}}-\frac{\left(v(1)\right)^{2}}{\zeta}
\]

\end_inset

Assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta=0$
\end_inset

 (infinite patent protection),
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v(\omega)=\frac{\zeta\omega}{\rho\zeta\omega+v(1)}\left(\frac{\phi_{i}-1}{\phi_{i}}\right)
\]

\end_inset

Replacing:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho v(1)=\left(\frac{\phi_{i}-1}{\phi_{i}}\right)+\frac{\left(\frac{\zeta\omega}{\rho\zeta\omega+v(1)}\left(\frac{\phi_{i}-1}{\phi_{i}}\right)-v(1)\right)^{2}}{2\alpha_{I}}-\frac{\left(v(1)\right)^{2}}{\zeta},
\]

\end_inset

Note:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{\zeta\omega}{\rho\zeta\omega+v(1)}\left(\frac{\phi_{i}-1}{\phi_{i}}\right)-v(1) & =\frac{\zeta\omega}{\rho\zeta\omega+v(1)}\left[\left(\frac{\phi_{i}-1}{\phi_{i}}\right)-\left(\frac{\rho\zeta\omega+v(1)}{\zeta\omega}\right)v(1)\right]\\
 & =\frac{\zeta\omega}{\rho\zeta\omega+v(1)}\left[\left(\frac{\phi_{i}-1}{\phi_{i}}\right)-\frac{\left(v(1)\right)^{2}}{\zeta\omega}-\rho v(1)\right]
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Which can be solved numerically.
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Now let us focus on incumbents' investment, which is proportional to 
\begin_inset Formula $v(\omega)-v(1)$
\end_inset

.
 Then, we obtain:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial}{\partial\omega}\frac{\left(v(\omega)-v(1)\right)}{\alpha_{I}}=\frac{\frac{\zeta\omega}{\rho\zeta\omega+v(1)}\left(\frac{\phi_{i}-1}{\phi_{i}}\right)-v(1)}{\alpha_{I}}=\frac{\zeta\left(\rho\zeta\omega+v(1)\right)-\zeta^{2}\rho\omega}{\alpha_{I}\left[\rho\zeta\omega+v(1)\right]^{2}}>0
\]

\end_inset

The same sign holds for 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta$
\end_inset

, the entry cost, although in that case 
\begin_inset Formula $v(1)$
\end_inset

 increases as well.
 Investment increases in the markups, as expected.
 As for entrants, investment increases like 
\begin_inset Formula $v(1).$
\end_inset

 Note:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho v(\omega)=\left(\frac{\phi_{i}-1}{\phi_{i}}\right)+\delta\left(v(1)-v(\omega)\right)-\frac{v(1)}{\zeta\omega}\left(v(\omega)\right)
\]

\end_inset

therefore
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\rho\left(v(\omega)-v(1)\right) & =\delta\left(v(1)-v(\omega)\right)-\frac{v(1)}{\zeta\omega}\left(v(\omega)\right)-\frac{\left(v(\omega)-v(1)\right)^{2}}{2\alpha_{I}}+\frac{v(1)}{\zeta}v(1)\\
\left(\rho+\delta+\frac{\left(v(\omega)-v(1)\right)}{2\alpha_{I}}\right)\left(v(\omega)-v(1)\right) & =\frac{v(1)}{\zeta}\left(v(1)-\frac{v(\omega)}{\omega}\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

This can be used to show that, if there is defensive investment, we have
 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega v(1)>v(\omega)$
\end_inset

.
 Note: to have positive research we must have:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v(\omega)-v(1)>0
\]

\end_inset

for 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{I}=0$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\rho v(1) & =\left(\frac{\phi_{i}-1}{\phi_{i}}\right)-x_{e,1}\left(v(1)\right)\\
\rho v(\omega) & =\left(\frac{\phi_{i}-1}{\phi_{i}}\right)+\delta\left(v(1)-v(\omega)\right)-x_{e,\omega}\left(v(\omega)\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\rho v(\omega)-\rho v(1) & =x_{e,1}v(1)-x_{e,\omega}v(\omega)\\
 & =\frac{v(1)}{\zeta}v(1)-\frac{v(1)}{\zeta\omega}v(\omega)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus, again, 
\begin_inset Formula $v(\omega)-v(1)>0$
\end_inset

 IFF 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega v(1)-v(\omega)>0$
\end_inset

.
 Is this always true? Suppose not, then the firm's investment has to be
 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

.
 In this case, the values to the firm are simply:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v(1)=\frac{m_{i}}{\rho+x_{e,1}},\ v(\omega)=\frac{m_{i}}{\rho+x_{e,\omega}},
\]

\end_inset

By the entrant's optimal solution we have that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{e,\omega}=\frac{x_{e,1}}{\omega}$
\end_inset

, and:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\omega v(1)=\frac{m_{i}}{\frac{\rho}{\omega}+x_{e,\omega}}>\frac{m_{i}}{\rho+x_{e,\omega}}=\nu(\omega),
\]

\end_inset

a contradiction.
 Given a optimal research effort 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, the firm's lifetime values are:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\left(\rho+x^{\star}+x_{e,1}\right)v(1) & =\left(\frac{\phi_{i}-1}{\phi_{i}}\right)-\alpha_{I}\frac{x^{\star,2}}{2}+x^{\star}\left(v(\omega)\right)\\
\left(\rho+\delta+x_{e,\omega}\right)v(\omega) & =\left(\frac{\phi_{i}-1}{\phi_{i}}\right)+\delta\left(v(1)\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus we have that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v(1)=\frac{\left(\frac{\phi_{i}-1}{\phi_{i}}\right)-\alpha_{I}\frac{x^{\star}}{2}+x^{\star}\left(v(\omega)\right)}{\left(\rho+x^{\star}+x_{e,1}\right)}
\]

\end_inset

In particular, in an equilibrium with positive research it holds:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
v(1) & >\frac{\left(\frac{\phi_{i}-1}{\phi_{i}}\right)}{\left(\rho+x_{e,1}\right)}\\
v(1) & >\frac{\left(\frac{\phi_{i}-1}{\phi_{i}}\right)}{\left(\rho+\frac{v(1)}{\zeta}\right)}\\
\rho v(1)+\zeta v(1)^{2} & >\zeta\left(\frac{\phi_{i}-1}{\phi_{i}}\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "lem: values"

\end_inset

Consider a steady state of the normalized one-sector model, and assume that
 defensive innovation is effective, 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega>1$
\end_inset

.
 Then, 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega v(1)>v(\omega)>v(1).$
\end_inset

 Around a steady state, the normalized values, 
\begin_inset Formula $v(1),v(\omega)$
\end_inset

, are increasing in the markup factor 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{i}=\frac{\phi_{i}-1}{\phi_{i}}$
\end_inset

, and
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial v(\omega)}{\partial m_{i}}>\frac{\partial v(1)}{\partial m_{i}}>0.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Stationary distribution
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The law of motion of the distribution across states satisfies:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\dot{\mu}_{1} & =-\left(x_{I}+x_{e,1}\right)\mu_{1}+\delta\mu_{\omega}+x_{e,\omega}\mu_{e,\omega}+x_{e,1}\mu_{e,1},\label{eq: dist1}\\
\dot{\mu}_{\omega} & =-\left(x_{e,\omega}+\delta\right)\mu_{\omega}+x_{I}\mu_{1},\label{eq: dist2}\\
\dot{\mu}_{e,1} & =-\left(x_{e,1}+x_{I}\right)\mu_{e,1}+x_{e,1}\mu_{1}+\delta\mu_{e,\omega},\label{eq: dist3}\\
\dot{\mu}_{e,\omega} & =-\left(x_{e,\omega}+\delta\right)\mu_{e,\omega}+x_{e,\omega}\mu_{\omega}+x_{I}\mu_{e,1},\label{eq: dist4}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{e,1},\mu_{e,\omega}$
\end_inset

 are the mass of entrants targeting products without a patent barrier, and
 with a patent barrier, respectively.
 Outflows from incumbent state 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 are given by the sum of successful incumbent defensive research, and eliminatio
n of incumbents by entrants.
 Inflows are given by expiration of patent protection moving incumbents
 in state 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 to state 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

, and successful entry.
 The incumbent state 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 loses mass from successful entrants and patent depreciation, and gains
 mass from successful defensive RD.
 The last two equations close the system by acknowledging that entrants
 lose mass from successful entry, and gain mass from displaced incumbents.
 The stationary distribution satisfies: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mu_{\omega} & =\frac{x_{I}}{x_{I}+x_{e,\omega}+\delta},\\
\mu_{1} & =\frac{x_{e,\omega}+\delta}{x_{I}+x_{e,\omega}+\delta},\\
\mu_{e,\omega} & =\frac{\omega x_{I}\mu_{1}+\left(\omega x_{e,\omega}+x_{I}\right)\mu_{\omega}}{\omega\left(x_{e,\omega}+\delta\right)+x_{I}},\\
\mu_{e,1} & =\frac{\omega\left(x_{e,\omega}+\delta\right)\mu_{1}+\delta\mu_{\omega}}{\omega\left(x_{e,\omega}+\delta\right)+x_{I}}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Total R&D
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Total R&D intensity is given by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu_{e,\omega}x_{e,\omega}+\mu_{e,1}x_{e,1}+\mu_{1}x_{I}
\]

\end_inset

By the optimal solution for entrants:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x_{e,1}=\omega x_{e,\omega},
\]

\end_inset

so total R&D effort is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
RD & =x_{e,\omega}\left(\mu_{e,\omega}+\omega\mu_{e,1}\right)+\mu_{1}x_{I}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Growth and R&D productivity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that productivity growth is accomplished solely through creative destructio
n by entrants.
 By Cobb-Douglas on the final good:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\log Y_{t} & =\int_{0}^{1}\log y_{t}\mathrm{d}i\\
g=\log\left(Y_{t+\Delta t}\right)-\log\left(Y_{t}\right) & =\eta\left[x_{e,\omega}\mu_{e,\omega}+x_{e,1}\mu_{e,1}\right].
\end{align*}

\end_inset

with inventors' productivity given by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{g}{L^{RD}}=\eta\frac{x_{e,\omega}\left(\mu_{e,\omega}+\omega\mu_{e,1}\right)}{\zeta\omega x_{e,\omega}\left(\mu_{e,\omega}+\mu_{e,1}\right)+\alpha_{I}\frac{x_{I}^{2}}{2}\mu_{1}}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Comparative statics in partial equilibrium
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The following proposition summarizes the comparative statics in partial
 equilibrium.
 
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The proof assumes 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta=0$
\end_inset

 for analytical simplicity, but this assumption does not seem necessary.
 All the following figures were obtained from a calibration with 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta>0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "prop: partialEq"

\end_inset

Consider the above model with a perfectly elastic production and R&D labor
 supply.
 Assume 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta=0,$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sqrt{\frac{\phi-1}{\phi}}\left(\frac{\alpha_{I}-\zeta\omega\left(\omega-1\right)}{\alpha_{I}\zeta\omega}\right)>\rho.
\]

\end_inset

 An increase in the markup factor 
\begin_inset Formula $m\equiv\frac{\phi-1}{\phi}$
\end_inset

, increases incumbents' and entrants' R&D, growth, and the incumbents' share
 of total R&D labor, and decreases inventor productivity, 
\begin_inset Formula $g/L^{RD}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:OneSecCS"

\end_inset

 displays the comparative statics for various aggregates of interest in
 an illustrative calibration for the single-sector model, where the supply
 of inventors is assumed to be perfectly elastic.
 In this setting, an increase in the markup factor 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\left(\phi-1\right)}{\phi}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Increases profits;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Increases both entrants' and incumbents' RD;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Increases the incumbents' RD share;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Increases sectoral growth;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Reduces sectoral RD productivity.
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Consider the ratio:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{\alpha_{I}\frac{x_{I}^{2}}{2}\mu_{1}}{\zeta\omega x_{e,\omega}\left(\mu_{e,\omega}+\mu_{e,1}\right)+\alpha_{I}\frac{x_{I}^{2}}{2}\mu_{1}} & =\\
\frac{\alpha_{I}\frac{x_{I}^{2}}{2}\mu_{1}}{\zeta\omega x_{e,\omega}\left(1+\frac{\left(\omega-1\right)x_{1}-\omega x_{e,\omega}}{\left(x_{I}+\omega x_{e,\omega}\right)}\mu_{1}\right)+\alpha_{I}\frac{x_{I}^{2}}{2}\mu_{1}} & =\\
\frac{\alpha_{I}\frac{x_{I}^{2}}{2}}{\zeta\omega x_{e,\omega}\left(\frac{\left(x_{I}+x_{e,\omega}\right)}{x_{e,\omega}}+\frac{\left(\omega-1\right)x_{1}-\omega x_{e,\omega}}{\left(x_{I}+\omega x_{e,\omega}\right)}\right)+\alpha_{I}\frac{x_{I}^{2}}{2}} & =\\
\frac{x_{I}}{\frac{2\zeta\omega}{\alpha_{I}}\frac{x_{e,\omega}}{x_{I}}\left(\frac{\left(1+\frac{x_{e,\omega}}{x_{I}}\right)}{\frac{x_{e,\omega}}{x_{I}}}+\frac{\left(\omega-1\right)-\omega\frac{x_{e,\omega}}{x_{I}}}{\left(1+\omega\frac{x_{e,\omega}}{x_{I}}\right)}\right)+x_{I}} & =\\
\frac{x_{I}}{\frac{2\zeta\omega}{\alpha_{I}}z\left(\frac{1+z}{z}+\frac{\left(\omega-1\right)-\omega z}{1+\omega z}\right)+x_{I}} & =
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Now the question is: how does the denominator change with 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

?
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\partial\frac{z\left(\frac{1+z}{z}+\frac{\left(\omega-1\right)-\omega z}{1+\omega z}\right)}{\partial z}m & =\left(\frac{1+z}{z}+\frac{\left(\omega-1\right)-\omega z}{1+\omega z}\right)+z\left(-\frac{1}{z^{2}}+\frac{-\omega\left(1+\omega z\right)+\omega^{2}z-\omega\left(\omega-1\right)}{\left(1+\omega z\right)^{2}}\right)\\
 & =\left(1+\frac{\left(\omega-1\right)-\omega z}{1+\omega z}\right)+\omega z\left(\frac{-\omega}{\left(1+\omega z\right)^{2}}\right)\\
 & =\left(\frac{\omega}{1+\omega z}\right)+\left(\frac{-\omega^{2}z}{\left(1+\omega z\right)^{2}}\right)\\
 & =\frac{\omega}{\left(1+\omega z\right)^{2}}>0
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Clearly, increase in growth is a byproduct of the perfectly elastic supply
 of inventors, who get drawn into R&D by increased profits.
 It is apparent that the increased in growth is driven by the increase in
 entrants' R&D activity, while the decrease in inventor productivity is
 driven by the increase in the inventors' share hired by monopolists engaged
 in defensive innovation.
\end_layout

